    content: 'Diary of Jacques de Voulon, Mage of New Averoigne\n\n14th day of Felmont, AC 1017\n\nQuelle humiliation! Once again, I find myself entangled in the strange ways of these diminutive folk, the Hin of the Five Shires. What should have been a simple afternoon of entertainment and a little joie de vivre has landed me in their ridiculous gaol. Why, you ask? For the grand crime of—wait for it—improving their atrocious local wine with a touch of magic. A harmless charm! But these Halflings, or Hin as they call themselves, seem to take offense at even the smallest display of wizardry.\n\nIt began innocently enough. I had wandered into one of their quaint villages, eager to rest after a long journey through their picturesque but dull countryside. The locals, ever curious, gathered around as I took a seat at the village square. Their wine—if you can call it that—was offered, and with a wave of my hand, I elevated it to something drinkable. The crowd marveled, but before I could enjoy their admiration, the Krondar arrived.*\n\nNow, these Krondar, deputies to their so-called Sheriffs, may be small in stature, but they wield an authority disproportionate to their size. They carry these curious implements, the Rods of Justice, iron rods that seem at first glance like ceremonial pieces. However, I soon learned they are anything but ceremonial. At a word from the Krondar, these rods can freeze a man where he stands, stopping him mid-motion, with a power far beyond what I expected from such a primitive tool. It was one of these Krondar who approached me, rod in hand, and declared that I was “disturbing the peace.” With barely a moment to explain myself, I was seized and carted off to their gaol—a miserable little cell hardly large enough for a broom closet, let alone a Glantrian wizard! I could hardly stretch my legs without bumping into the walls, and the bed—if you could call it that—was fit only for their kind. I spent the night cramped, stooped, and sore, with only the sounds of their village festivities to torment me.\n\nThe next morning, I was brought before the Sheriff, the one to whom these Krondar answer. He carried a Rod of Justice as well, a symbol of their authority. The Sheriff, at least, had some semblance of humor, laughing off my “crime” and releasing me after a stern lecture about the dangers of magic in the Shires. He even thanked me for amusing his people, though he warned me never to cast spells so lightly in his land again. Apparently, they take no risks with sorcery here, even if it’s for something as harmless as wine.\n\nI must admit, their system of law is impressive in its way. The Krondar, for all their size, act with a precision and confidence that belies their stature. And those Rods of Justice—remarkable tools, capable of stopping even the most defiant of men without drawing blood. Still, I will tread carefully should I pass through these lands again, for while the Halflings may be charming, their laws are no laughing matter. And as for their wine? No amount of magic can save it.',
